Spring & Spring Boot – Beginner Notes
1. Introduction to Spring

Spring is a Java framework used to build enterprise-level applications.

It provides support for:

Dependency management

Web development

Database access

Security

Core idea:
Spring helps developers write loosely coupled and maintainable code.

2. Introduction to Spring Boot

Spring Boot is built on top of Spring to simplify application development.

It provides:

Faster development

Minimal configuration

Reduced boilerplate code

Concept:
Spring = Core framework
Spring Boot = Simplified version with ready-to-use setup

3. Spring vs Spring Boot
Feature                 	Spring	                         Spring Boot
Setup	                    Complex                           	Easy
Configuration          	Manual (XML/Java)	                 Auto-configuration
Server                 	External server required	         Embedded server
Development                 Speed	Slower	                   Faster
Boilerplate Code	              More	                        Less

4. Spring Boot Core Features
Auto Configuration

Automatically configures the application based on dependencies.

Starter Dependencies

Predefined dependency sets:

spring-boot-starter-web

spring-boot-starter-data-jpa

Embedded Server

No need to install external servers like Tomcat.

Production Ready Features

Includes monitoring, metrics, and health checks.

5. IOC (Inversion of Control)

IOC means the framework controls object creation instead of the developer.

Without Spring:

Car car = new Car();

With Spring:
Spring creates and manages objects.

Benefits:

Reduces tight coupling

Improves flexibility

6. DI (Dependency Injection)

DI is a technique where dependencies are provided to a class instead of being created inside it.

Example:

class Engine {}

class Car {
    Engine engine;

    Car(Engine engine) {
        this.engine = engine;
    }
}

Spring injects the required dependency automatically.

7. IOC vs DI
IOC	DI
Concept	Implementation
Controls object creation	Injects dependencies
High-level idea	Practical usage
8. Autowiring

Autowiring is automatic dependency injection performed by Spring.

Example:

import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;

@Component
class Engine {}

@Component
class Car {

    @Autowired
    Engine engine;
}
9. Why Autowiring?

Removes manual object creation

Reduces boilerplate code

Improves readability

Easier maintenance

